Comment: @himanshu keshtwal when one primary key is not enough in case of that we set 2 primary keys and we call it as composite key . Name: GazbertUK
Comment:
Tried several times to put up a solution for the POPSQL issues people are having, i.e.: 
Can't connect to local MySQL server through socket '/run/mysqld/mysqld.sock' (2)
and not being able to connect the next day, and connecting to the company DB,
But my comments keep disappearing - so I'm going to try posting it sentence by sentence as replies to this comment. Let me know if it has worked.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 9. The connection name field should be a name you give to the connection, make it something meaningful so you remember what it's for later on .e.g. Giraffe tutorial.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: @Nafisa Zaman Did you get it to work? Good luck.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 12. Now leave the other settings alone, and click on the 'Test' button at the bottom of page - hopefully you should get a green Looks good message at the top of the page. Now click the Save button followed by the Connect button, which will bring up the SQL page.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 11.  In the Username/Password you need to put in 'root' as the username, and then use your MySQL password that you set up in step 2. For 'Connection Type' the slider button needs to be slid right so it turns blue.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 10. In Hostname use 'localhost' and in port '3306'. The database field needs to be the name of the database that you created earlier in MySQL - so if you're following the video, it would be 'giraffe'.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 8. You should now see a list of connection(s), if there's something there that says giraffe or has your name then that might be the connection for your MySQL sesssion. Click on that and you should see and Edit Connection screen. If there's nothing there, or nothing you recognize then click on the 'Add new connection' button at top right.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 7. If you don't have connections available, you can click the connection icon, and then 'Manage Connections', or you can click on the Account button (bottom left of screen with the initial of you username) and click 'Manage Connections' from there.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 6. When you get into POPSQL it was a bit confusing as for me there was a load of random SQL statements in the panel to the left of center. You can ignore this stuff, I think it maybe examples from MySQL. At the top right of the screen under the Green Run and Blue Share buttons, there are a couple of icons and words - these are the name of the connection - with a MySQL icon,  and the name of the database, that the connection connects to. If you left-click the connection it will show any available connections.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: 4. Now, still in MySQL type: use giraffe; and enter, then type: create table student (student_id int primary key, name varchar(20) ); and enter again. Type : describe students;. Hopefully this all worked and you know you've got MySQL working ok.

Name: GazbertUK
Comment: @Nafisa Zaman put root in the username, and slide the button to the right that is just under neath. Then click test at the bottom.

Name: Mev
Comment:
@Ishtiaque Hossain Try this:


In the SQL shell, you first need to change from JS to SQL, and connect to the root@localhost

>Mysql JS>  \sql
>Mysql SQL>  \connect root@localhost
>password

Then create the database:

> CREATE DATABASE giraffe;


Then when you create the connection in PopSQL go to advanced options and enable 'Connect directly from my computer'.

Name: Ishtiaque Hossain
Comment: @Mev Tried both but unfortunately PopSQL can't connect to the server in my computer

Name: Mev
Comment:
When you go to manage connections in PopSQL to create the MySQL connection go to advanced options and enable 'Connect directly from my computer'.

If that doesn't work try entering 'use giraffe' (or whatever you named your database) in the MySQL command line client.

Hopefully that should fix your problem!

1:15:00
Here are some problems that I encountered during setup and their solution:
In the SQL shell, you first need to change from JS to SQL, and connect to the root@localhost

>Mysql JS>  \sql
>Mysql SQL>  \connect root@localhost
>password

Then create the dataset:

> CREATE DATASET giraffe;

Then you need to go to popsql, and connect to this dataset, 
in the main window, on the top left corner, there is a blueish icon, click on it and click on manage connections
click on New Connection on the bottom left corner in the pop up window
select the type to be MySQL
enter the parameters like the instruction on the video and click connect

Name: Rohit Halwai
Comment:
If you are having trouble in the installation or running of POPSQL in the windows follow the steps
1. You need to create an account to get the download option for windows from the website so just create account using Windows
2.  After installation the Home screen of the application will look way different than that in this video, to get all the info in your POPsql home screen follow this steps
3. On the Top Mid of the screen you will see something called Popsql sample data, hover over it and click on manage connections when it pops out while hovering over it
4. In the Type section select MySql and enter all other details as shown in the video
5. Also make sure before doing all that your MySql should be up and running, do not close the Mysql application. 
Hope it helped, It took me a lot of time to figure this part out.

Name: Francisco Chavez
Comment:
SSN don't uniquely identity people in the U.S. Not only is is possible for multiple people to have the same SSN, but it IS an actually thing that happens from time to time. Sometimes, it's more than two people that share an SSN. Systems that can't tell that more than one person can have the same SSN have created legal issues for people. On top of that, it is possible for a person to have their SSN legally changed. One of the common solutions to having too many people with your SSN, is to have your SSN legally changed. So, it is possible for people outside of Witness Protection to have more than one SSN throughout their lives. Getting your SSN changed creates all sorts of issues for the person that had it changed because it makes it nearly impossible to quickly and easily link them to their degrees, diplomas, and certifications when doing a background search. Not having a background can cause issues when you're trying to get something like a job or a loan. But, sharing a SSN with someone with a bad credit history or a wrap sheet can also cause those same issues.

Long story short, NEVER use SSN as a person's key-identifier in your database.

Comment:
4:12:37.I feel like u used one-to-many relation instead of one to one 
to use one to one 
CREATE TABLE branch (
  branch_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
  branch_name VARCHAR(40),
  mgr_id INT UNIQUE,
  mgr_start_date DATE,
  FOREIGN KEY(mgr_id) REFERENCES employee(emp_id) ON DELETE SET NULL
);
this schema should give u a one-to-one relation.

really loved the amazing tutorial, I think I have almost watched all of the mike Danes beginner tutorials, thank you mike dane. for this amazing tutorial as always.

Name: Tech HackZ
Comment:
in full join use union 
select employee.emp_id , employee.first_name , branch.branch_name
from branch
RIGHT join employee
ON employee.emp_id= branch.mgr_id
UNION
select employee.emp_id , employee.first_name , branch.branch_name
from branch
left join employee
ON employee.emp_id= branch.mgr_id;

Nested Queries...
assume we know the ID of Michael Scott. 
Nononononono. Assume I don't know his ID.

Boring code below.

SELECT client.client_name AS 'Michael Scotts clients'
FROM client
WHERE client.branch_id IN (
    SELECT branch.branch_id
    FROM branch
    WHERE branch.mgr_id IN (
        SELECT employee.emp_id
        FROM employee
        WHERE employee.first_name = 'Michael' AND employee.last_name = 'Scott'
    )
);

Name: Ade Enga
Comment: If anyone is experiencing the command line client refusing to open, I noticed that by default some vital steps were skipped during installation. Search your apps for the "MySQL Installer - Community" and open it up. You'll then see the Server and Shell which were installed. Click on reconfigure for the server and then skip past the first page with next. Then you should arrive at the page to choose a password (you need this set up, otherwise the client won't load - this part was skipped during my initial set up). Go ahead and choose the password and then next, next, next, etc. until you've executed the changes. Click finish and then run the Command Line Client again from the start up. You'll then be asked for that password. Then you're set.

You could use a JOIN instead of nested queries like this : 
SELECT employee.emp_id, employee.first_name,employee.last_name, works_with.total_sales FROM employee

just wanted to ADD, if you have installed MySQL on VM and installed POPSQL on windows and trying to connect:
please allow the IP of your windows machine in the DB and then connect.
[root@localhost ~]# mysql -u root -p
mysql> GRANT ALL ON *.* to 'root'@'172.25.10.1' IDENTIFIED BY 'Redhat@1234';
mysql> FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
mysql> exit


after this, you should be able to establish connection

Comment:
For macOS Catalina (and later) users, to tell your mac where is MySQL is installed, use the following command on the terminal instead:¬†
1. echo 'export PATH=/usr/local/mysql/bin:$PATH' >> ~/.zprofile
2. . ~/.zprofile
Basically, you change what Mike wrote ~/.bash_profile to ~/.zprofile. This is all because mac now use zsh as the default interactive shell.

Mac Catalina's default terminal is zsh. So if your terminal is zsh, you'd probably want to put this in your terminal to initialize mysql command:

echo 'export PATH=/usr/local/mysql/bin:$PATH' >> ~/.zshrc

(Note that file name is zshrc, not bash_profile)

Name: Tea Sea
Comment:
Even though there's technically not a full outer join in MySQL, you can always muster your way to it by using the Union, right join, and left join combinations together. In the example that was used in the video, this will produce a full outer join in MySQL - incase anyone wants to see how it'll populate:

SELECT employee.emp_id, employee.first_name, branch.branch_name
FROM employee
LEFT JOIN branch
ON employee.emp_id = branch.mgr_id
UNION
SELECT employee.emp_id, employee.first_name, branch.branch_name
FROM employee
RIGHT JOIN branch
ON employee.emp_id = branch.mgr_id

I hope this helps someone in the future.

Name: Joe Obligar
Comment: For windows, all you need to do is go to the path where the "bin" is inside mysql folder. Your mysql folder is probably located in your local disk C, then go inside program files, then MySQL folder, then MySQL Server, then bin (Should look like this or something similar : C:\Program Files\MySQL\MySQL Server 8.0\bin). Right-click on the bin where on the breadcrumb navigation up top is and copy the address, then on your terminal type cd, then a space, then paste the address and hit enter. Then type in what was in the video which was "mysql -u root -p" then enter your password. Hope this helped.

Name: Michael Thompson
Comment:
Just a comment on 'On Delete'. I never cascade delete, and almost never delete rows. It's far safer to have an attribute that is something like 'isCurrent' (caption Current?). When that binary is set to false, then you have a query that only pulls current = true, and that is what you normally access, not going to the table directly. That way you don't get in trouble with internal revenue when they're checking your books over, and you don't have any broken links, for example, branchId = 2 in another table when there is no branchId 2 in the branch table.
While deleting rows is a REALLY bad idea, archiving is sometimes a good idea. If your table gets 'too big', you can shift records off to an archived version of the table, and delete the rows from the original table. For example, you may want to do this for sales data that is, say, more than two years old. You still wouldn't delete the sales person, or the product name, etc., but you would archive this sales data, because a) you probably won't be wanting to access it any time soon and b) if you do want to access it you can always restore it to the main table (or merge a query on the archive table), but if you mess with the parent tables (sales person, products) by archiving rows your child table won't know where to go to get the names, and you've lost referential integrity.

Comment:
I ran into problems on Triggers in the Command Line Client. If you get a '1359 table already exists' error message after fixing a typo in the trigger when you re-input the information into the command line client, one should delete the trigger in popsql before trying to re input the information into the clc again. Also, if mysql disappears in the clc and you get this -> 
instead of mysql>
 just type in \c, and this will erase what you wrote prior, and make mysql appear again. I'm a novice, so I would imagine that other novices may run into problems such as this as well and not know what's happening.

Name: Eric Adell
Comment:
You can do a full outer join (3:10:53)  by taking the union of a left join and a right join: 

SELECT employee.emp_id,employee.first_name, branch.branch_name
FROM employee
LEFT JOIN branch
ON employee.emp_id = branch.mgr_id
UNION
SELECT employee.emp_id,employee.first_name, branch.branch_name
FROM employee
RIGHT JOIN branch
ON employee.emp_id = branch.mgr_id;

Name: Nephy Nomer
Comment:
Excellent class. Even though I started with ZERO SQL knowledge, I managed to create more complex query based on the lesson here. Thought I'd share the queries I've built.


The following query takes the data from the sample database, and extracts the Employee ID, Forename, Surname, Branch and Total sum of sales per staff member.


SELECT Employee.emp_id AS ID, Employee.first_name AS Forename, Employee.last_name AS Surname, Branch.branch_name AS Branch, SUM(Works_With.TOTAL_SALES) AS Sales
FROM Employee
LEFT JOIN Branch
on Employee.branch_id = branch.BRANCH_id
RIGHT JOIN Works_With
on Employee.emp_id = Works_With.emp_id
GROUP BY Employee.emp_id
ORDER BY TOTAL_SALES DESC;




This query changes the reported data to include the client ID and no longer groups the total sales figures by employee. Note that you can rename a column using the 'text' method to include spaces in the column title, such as 'Client Name' rather than Client_Name.
SELECT Employee.emp_id AS ID, Employee.first_name AS Forename, Employee.last_name AS Surname, Branch.branch_name AS Branch, Works_With.TOTAL_SALES AS Sales, Client.client_name AS 'Client Name'
FROM Employee
LEFT JOIN Branch
on Employee.branch_id = branch.BRANCH_id
RIGHT JOIN Works_With
on Employee.emp_id = Works_With.emp_id
LEFT JOIN Client
ON Works_With.CLIENT_id=Client.CLIENT_id
ORDER BY TOTAL_SALES DESC;


Good luck learning. I'm off to find the next lesson!

Name: Mon Day
Comment: 36:20 Primary keys columns, either alone or combined with other primary key columns, normally do not use mixed case (as opposed to upper or lower case) or whitespaces, in their values, as this is prone to errors. So, the "Hammer Mill" value typically would be stored as "hammermill", or "HAMMERMILL". All is much easier if one agrees to not use mixed case, or whitespaces, in all primary key columns. Obviously, attribute columns - which is the data a database is about, have information in any desired case, and whitespaces as desired.

Name: Ken Haley
Comment:
Having taught many technical topics myself over the years (I'm 71 now), I have some suggestions: You've obviously done a tremendous amount of work on this, and I don't mean to take anything away from that.  But...

Try not to be so wordy and repetitive.  Avoid unnecessary words and phrases, like "basically", and "go ahead and..".  It's better to talk slower and say whatever you want to say ONCE.   If you want to emphasize a point, say it slowly and perhaps in two or three DIFFERENT ways.  But just repeating the same thing the same way two or three times doesn't help make your point--it just tends to be boring.  Be brief. Less is more. Remember...the viewer can always pause and back up the video if they miss something.

Having said that, your content and organization is great--as many of your viewers have already attested.  But, believe me, your courses will be much more effective and popular if you follow the simple style rules above.

Name: Mr J
Comment:
Here's how you create a database from scrarch:
1. Think what tables you're gonna need
2. Plan what you're doing by drawing the tables on a piece of paper with a pencil
3. Go to a program on your computer like Toad Data Modeler for example and make the tables there
4. Once you're done there generate a ddl script. The ddl script you generate has sql queries for the tables you made in Toad Data Modeler
5. Choose a DBMS(Database Managment System) like PG Admin, Heroku, Elephant SQL,... to host your database there

Hope this helped a little

Comment:
Great tutorial.  Just wanted to point out an error at the REGEXP practice question.  For the first part of the question you ask for a query that returns a first name that ARE 'ELKA' or 'AMBUR', but your solution with the pipe would return results that CONTAIN those strings.  In the context of your databases, you get the same results, but this is an important distinction. The correct solution would be with the IN operator--

SELECT *
FROM customers
WHERE first_name IN (‚ÄòELKA‚Äô, ‚ÄòAMBUR‚Äô);

Name: Maestro
Comment:
It took me 2,5 hours to find a solution to this. So here it is for everyone: 

When you have the same problem, you need to:
Rashaad Griggs
if you struggling to connect to your local server, go to your C drive (local diskdrive) - Program Files (x86) - MySQL - MySQL installer for windows - MySQL.Installer.Console and install it manually.
Also:
When reconfiguring if it says your port is already in use, you need to turn the MySQL off first. To do that: type "services" into windows search bar in the bottom left and click on services, window with a list opens, find MySQL, left click and select stop. Then follow the advice above again.

Comment: Let me make a comment to everyone ... 12:10 ... Mine had a lot of things that failed.  But, they did not complete.  So, I think he made a mistake in saying which one to download.  If you have a problem and get a lot of FAILED (instead of COMPLETE).  Then, do this.  Go back to the site ( 10:39) and DO NOT SELECT THE FIRST ONE, select the second one (343.3Mb).  The second one is a FULL INSTALLER and the first one is a WEB INSTALLER.  So, you might have something setup where it can't get through your firewall or something, because you have Win10 and have Virus Protection turned on.  So, use the second one, and it seems to work better.  When you start the Installer the second time, tell it to DELETE EVERYTHING off, then start again.  Then, it should work this time.  I hope this helps someone.  Let me know if it helps you.  And, Mosh might need to update the video or put this somewhere in Description.

Name: Elliot
Comment:
Hey, for the deleting rows code at 3:06:40 you will be given an Error Code: 1241. Operand should contain 1 column(s). This is because the subquery is returning multiple columns when it should only be returning the client id. To fix this issue all we have to do is change the * to client_id in the subquery. Your code will look like this: 

USE sql_invoicing;

DELETE FROM invoices
WHERE client_id = (
					SELECT client_id
					FROM clients
					WHERE name = "Myworks"
)

This will fix your operand error, hope this helps :)

Then open MySQL Workbench and select the Open SQL file icon (the 2nd one from the left in the tool bar at the top), at which point you select the database file from the list that pops up. Then click on the execute (lightning bolt) icon in the query editor (area in the middle of window). Lastly, click on the refresh icon in the Schemas tab of the navigator panel on the left. Hope that helps.

Comment: Replace all of utf8mb4_0900_ai_ci to utf8mb4_general_ci. This can happen, when you use a database, which has been created with a newer version of MySQL, with an older MySQL server version. Name: level 1
Comment: @Hasan Emin Balkaya Thanks for help means a lot can you help me with one more doubt in compound join I tried executing the query he wrote I got only column names no records in table was that suppose to happen ? Name: Hasan Emin Balkaya
Comment:
On your first code, you order your output by 'total price' which is a string, this doesn't have any influence on sorting. You will get the same result if you remove that line. On the second code, total_price is the variable you define on your first line so it is taken into consideration. However, you should order your data on descending total price (Highest to lowest). Following is the solution:

SELECT *, quantity * unit_price AS total_price
FROM order_items
WHERE order_id=2
ORDER BY total_price DESC

Name: Manish Lopes
Comment: Thanks  it was a good session how do i find no of tables in a database

Name: edureka!
Comment:
Hi Manish, You can use INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES to retrieve information about your database tables. It returns one row for each table in the current database for which the current user has permissions. The following query, therefore, will return the number of tables in the specified database:

USE MyDatabase
SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM INFORMATION_SCHEMA.TABLES
WHERE TABLE_TYPE = 'BASE TABLE
